38 (b) This subsection does not apply to a person described in
39 subsection (d), (e), or (f). A person released on parole remains on
40 parole from the date of release until the person's fixed term expires,
41 unless the person's parole is revoked or the person is discharged from
42 that term by the parole board. In any event, if the person's parole is not
HB 1258—LS 6822/DI 151

37
1 revoked, the parole board shall discharge the person after the period set
2 under subsection (a) or the expiration of the person's fixed term,
3 whichever is shorter.
4 (c) A person whose parole is revoked shall be imprisoned for all or
5 part of the remainder of the person's fixed term. However, the person
6 shall again be released on parole when the person completes that
7 remainder, less the credit time the person has earned since the
8 revocation. The parole board may reinstate the person on parole at any
9 time after the revocation.
10 (d) This subsection does not apply to a person who is a sexually
11 violent predator under IC 35-38-1-7.5. When a sex offender (as defined
12 in IC 11-8-8-4.5) completes the sex offender's fixed term of
13 imprisonment, less credit time earned with respect to that term, the sex
14 offender shall be placed on parole for not more than ten (10) years.
15 (e) This subsection applies to a person who:
16 (1) is a sexually violent predator under IC 35-38-1-7.5;
17 (2) has been convicted of murder (IC 35-42-1-1); or
18 (3) has been convicted of voluntary manslaughter (IC 35-42-1-3).
19 When a person described in this subsection completes the person's
20 fixed term of imprisonment, less credit time earned with respect to that
21 term, the person shall be placed on parole for the remainder of the
22 person's life.
23 (f) This subsection applies to a parolee in another jurisdiction who
24 is a person described in subsection (e) and whose parole supervision is
25 transferred to Indiana from another jurisdiction. In accordance with
26 IC 11-13-4-1(2) (Interstate Compact for Out-of-State Probationers and
27 Parolees) and rules adopted under Article VII (d)(8) of the Interstate
28 Compact for Adult Offender Supervision (IC 11-13-4.5), a parolee who
29 is a person described in subsection (e) and whose parole supervision is
30 transferred to Indiana is subject to the same conditions of parole as a
31 person described in subsection (e) who was convicted in Indiana,
32 including:
33 (1) lifetime parole (as described in subsection (e)); and
34 (2) the requirement that the person wear a monitoring device (as
35 described in IC 35-38-2.5-3) that can transmit information
36 twenty-four (24) hours each day regarding a person's precise
37 location, if applicable.
38 (g) If a person being supervised on lifetime parole as described in
39 subsection (e) is also required to be supervised by a court, a probation
40 department, a community corrections program, a community transition
41 program, or another similar program upon the person's release from
42 imprisonment, the parole board may:
HB 1258—LS 6822/DI 151

38
1 (1) supervise the person while the person is being supervised by
2 the other supervising agency; or
3 (2) permit the other supervising agency to exercise all or part of
4 the parole board's supervisory responsibility during the period in
5 which the other supervising agency is required to supervise the
6 person, if supervision by the other supervising agency will be, in
7 the opinion of the parole board:
8 (A) at least as stringent; and
9 (B) at least as effective;
10 as supervision by the parole board.
11 (h) The parole board is not required to supervise a person on
12 lifetime parole during any period in which the person is imprisoned.
13 However, upon the person's release from imprisonment, the parole
14 board shall recommence its supervision of a person on lifetime parole.
15 (i) If a court orders the parole board to place a sexually violent
16 predator whose sentence does not include a commitment to the
17 department of correction on lifetime parole under IC 35-38-1-29, the
18 parole board shall place the sexually violent predator on lifetime parole
19 and supervise the person in the same manner in which the parole board
20 supervises a sexually violent predator on lifetime parole whose
21 sentence includes a commitment to the department of correction.
22 (j) Time served while confined to a jail or prison does not count
23 toward time served on parole.
24 SECTION 28. IC 36-1-26-4, AS ADDED BY P.L.182-2018,
25 SECTION 6, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
26 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 4. (a) Not later than November 1, 2018, a unit
27 shall revise its licensing requirements to the extent necessary to
28 explicitly list the crimes that will disqualify an individual from
29 receiving a license required by the unit. The unit may not:
30 (1) use nonspecific terms, such as moral turpitude or good
31 character, as a licensing requirement; or
32 (2) consider an arrest that does not result in a conviction.
33 (b) A unit's use of an individual's conviction of a crime as a
34 disqualifying criminal conviction is limited to a crime that is
35 specifically and directly related to the duties and responsibilities of the
36 occupation or profession for which the individual is applying for or
37 holds a license.
38 (c) If an applicant has a disqualifying criminal history, the unit shall
39 consider the following in determining whether to deny a license to the
40 applicant, based on a clear and convincing showing:
41 (1) The nature and seriousness of the crime for which the
42 individual was convicted.
HB 1258—LS 6822/DI 151

39
1 (2) The passage of time since the commission of the crime.
2 (3) The relationship of the crime to the ability, capacity, and
3 fitness required to perform the duties and discharge the
4 responsibilities of the occupation.
5 (4) Evidence of rehabilitation or treatment undertaken by the
6 individual that might mitigate against a direct relation to the
7 ability, capacity, and fitness required to perform the duties and
8 discharge the responsibilities of the occupation.
9 (d) If an individual has a disqualifying criminal conviction, the
10 period of disqualification may not exceed five (5) years after the date
11 of the conviction or release from incarceration, whichever is later,
12 unless the individual:
13 (1) was convicted of a crime of violence (as defined by
14 IC 35-50-1-2(a)); IC 35-31.5-2-79);
15 (2) was convicted of an offense relating to a criminal sexual act
16 (as defined by IC 35-31.5-2-216); or
17 (3) is convicted of a second or subsequent crime during the
18 disqualification period.
19 SECTION 29. IC 36-8-26-6, AS ADDED BY P.L.103-2022,
20 SECTION 6, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
21 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 6. Before November 1, 2023, and before
22 November 1 of every year thereafter, the board shall send a report of its
23 activities to the legislative council. The report must be in an electronic
24 format under IC 5-14-6 and include the following information:
25 (1) A copy of every interoperability agreement entered into or
26 renewed in the past year.
27 (2) A list of all:
28 (A) Part One crimes (based on the reporting methodology of
29 the Federal Bureau of Investigation); and
30 (B) crimes of violence (as defined in IC 35-50-1-2(a));
31 IC 35-31.5-2-79);
32 committed in the downtown district within the previous five (5)
33 years.
34 (3) The crime clearance rates for each crime described in
35 subdivision (2).
36 (4) A list of every major event that took place in the downtown
37 district within the previous year.
38 (5) The number of times a law enforcement agency made a
39 referral to, or requested assistance from, a social worker or mental
40 health services provider (including a provider who specializes in
41 addiction services).
42 (6) A completed crime perception survey for the previous year
HB 1258—LS 6822/DI 151

40
1 (based on the survey prepared by Downtown Indy, Inc.).
